    {
      "title": "Corner Case Detection in Autonomous Driving With Deep Learning",
      "abstract": "Object detection serves as the fundamental cornerstone of autonomous driving perception technology. 
By precisely and promptly identifying traffic participants in the vicinity of the vehicle, the object detection model d
elivers safety warnings and protection to the driver. Corner case detection in autonomous driving remains a critical an
d challenging area of research due to the complex environmental conditions and irregular object shapes involved, such a
s a self-driving car dealing with sudden pedestrians, non-standard traffic signs, road works, and animals crossing the 
road. These scenarios demand higher robustness and accuracy from object detection algorithms. Existing research often i
nadequately addresses these complexities, resulting in suboptimal performance in real-world applications. This study de
lves into corner case detection in autonomous driving and proposes an improved objective detection model based on You O
nly Look Once version 10 (YOLOv10). In this paper, the Depth-Wise Convolution (DWConv) and Omni-Dimensional Convolution
 (ODConv) are integrated into the backbone and head modules of the original YOLOv10 algorithm. Comparative experiments 
demonstrate that these improvements significantly enhance the original YOLOv10鈥檚 ability to detect complex corner cases
, achieving a 2.9% average precision (AP) improvement and a 24.5% mean average recall (mAR) improvement on the widely-u
sed Corner Case Dataset (CODA). The results indicate that the modified YOLOv10 maintains competitive inference speed wh
ile providing higher precision, showcasing the potential of targeted architectural enhancements in improving corner cas
e detection for autonomous driving. This advancement contributes to improving the efficiency and safety of self-driving
 vehicle operations.",
