      "title": "A Improved YOLOv11n Network Integrated with GAM for Five-State Classification of Yellow Peaches",
      "abstract": "In the visual system of yellow peach harvesting robots, accurately identifying the ripeness level an
d surface condition of the fruit is a core prerequisite for achieving precise harvesting and quality grading. To addres
s issues such as low recognition accuracy for soiled categories and the ease of confusion between soiled and ripe featu
res in the multi-dimensional classification of yellow peaches under complex orchard environments, this paper proposes a
n enhanced detection method for yellow peach conditions based on an improved YOLOv11n. This method introduces a Global 
Attention Mechanism (GAM) within the backbone, enhancing the extraction and discrimination of fine-grained features thr
ough dual-path feature enhancement in both the channel and spatial dimensions. The improved model was trained and valid
ated using a constructed yellow peach image dataset comprising five status categories (containing $\\mathbf{2, 0 7 1}$ 
images and 9,713 annotated yellow peach bounding boxes). The results show that the improved model achieved a mAP@ 0.5 o
f 81.7 % on the validation set, which is $\\mathbf{1. 6}$ percentage points higher than that of the baseline model. Con
fusion matrix analysis reveals that the category confusion between soiled and ripe yellow peaches is significantly alle
viated. The classification accuracy of the soiled category is increased from $\\mathbf{4 5 \\%}$ to $\\mathbf{6 2 \\%}$
, false positive rates are substantially reduced, and classification robustness is enhanced. This method demonstrates s
ignificant advantages in mitigating category confusion (such as between soiled and ripe fruit) and provides a technical
 reference with high accuracy and real-time performance for the visual perception systems of orchard harvesting robots.
