    {
      "title": "A Systematic Data-Driven Analysis of Deep Neural Networks for Helmet Detection",
      "abstract": "In our country the helmet detection in motorcycle riders imposes a significant safety paradigm that 
needs an efficient monitoring system. Advancement in automated helmet detection methodologies can crucially improve pre
cision, hence minimizing accidents. These sophisticated models reduce human labor and enhance accuracy for efficient de
tection of paving methods for a better and accident-free environment. Multiple pre-processing techniques such as image 
resizing, bounding box conversion, and normalization were used in this study. Some of the data argumentation techniques
 with ten significantly improved model techniques were also implied for handling dynamic real-world situations. Ten mod
els were trained: YOLOv8n, ResNet50, Vision Transformer (ViT-Tiny), DeiT-Tiny, Swin Transformer, EfficientNet-B0, Mobil
eNetV3, ConvNeXt-Tiny, DINOv2-Small, and MaxViT-Tiny. Results show that DINOv2-Small achieved the highest test accuracy
 of 87.82% with a loss of 0.3042 followed by ViT-Tiny having 86.08% accuracy. The study provides practical knowledge fo
r real world safety applications.",
